Show HN: Monoid (YC S21) – Open-Source Data Privacy Automation
text:
Hi everyone! Excited to share what we’ve been working on for the past few months. Monoid is a self-hosted, open-source first platform for automating data privacy requirements.

At Monoid’s core are open-source privacy connectors with DB’s, warehouses, SaaS tools, and more. These connectors let organizations automate user data export/deletion (for DSARs) and scan for/map PII.

We think that going open-source improves on the privacy software category meaningfully:

- Monoid is extensible by design, so if there are missing integrations for needed data silos, it’s straightforward to add custom connectors - Monoid is locally deployable and thus truly private.

You can play around with a read-only demo account at https://demo.monoid.co, and sign up for our cloud offering at https://app.monoid.co.

We’re adding code-scanning, consent management, and more in the coming weeks. Feedback would be much appreciated!

Ask HN: Do wrist movements provide enough energy to run a smartwatch?
text:
I currently use two watches, one automatic mechanical watch that always has enough energy in its spring, as long as I use it during the week, and one cheap smartwatch that cannot last much more than a day.

I like both and wondered whether arm movements provide enough energy after conversion to run a smartwatch with basic features, such as Bluetooth music, GPS tracking, heart rate sensor, and vectorial maps...

That would be a smartwatch that doesn't have to be charged ever and have cool mechanical engineering too.

Show HN: Columnar store for fast, lightweight logging
text:
Founder here,

Parseable is a lightweight log ingestion and query engine written in Rust. Parseable can ingest data from existing logging agents (FluentBit, LogStash, Vector, syslog-ng and more) using HTTP + JSON output. Ingested logs are stored as semi-indexed Parquet files (on disk or S3).

You can query the data with builtin query engine using SQL or use a query engines of choice like Spark, Presto, Trino and so on.

We also developed a Grafana data source plugin that lets you visualise log data via Grafana. Sample dashboard link in readme.

As log data grew, our industry has responded with SaaS and fully managed offerings, but if you're looking for freedom, interoperability and full control over your data - there are no great options. With Parseable, we are looking to provide an strong, viable and FOSS alternative.

How can a software engineer help the war in Ukraine?
text:
As a software engineer with some spare time, I've considered assisting the Ukrainian side, but don't know where to start.

- Does open source intelligence[0] need any help? Better ML models for detecting military objects in videos? Improvements to geolocation? Better user interfaces? Better back end infrastructure?

- Are there any open source libraries used by the Ukrainian side (and not by the Russian side) with open bugs?

- Something else?

I've donated money, and could do other things that don't use my programming skills. But it seems using my skills could make for a greater impact.

I don't have security clearance or any other connection, I'm just a random dev living in the West.

[0] https://www.economist.com/leaders/2023/01/18/fighting-in-the-fog-of-data-in-ukraine

Show HN: View Your Social Networks on an iPod
text:
Hey HN!

This is iPod Social, an interactive iPod interface made with JavaScript. (thanks to Tanner Villarete).

With iPod Social you can view Hacker News, view Tweets from a specific user, view Instagram from a specific user, and watch YouTube's most popular videos.

I hope it adds a bit of nostalgia to the experience of using the web.

Let me know if you have any questions or suggestions, I'd love to hear your feedback.
